<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Ceanothus leucodermis </i>rapidly sprouts from root crowns when branches are removed by fire (or other disturbance) over most of its range, but plants north of Tulare Co. do not sprout (Sampson and Jespersen 1963). Heat from fire stimulates germination by increasing permeability to water. Stands develop quickly from both sprouting and seeding, and they self-thin for the first 30 years of growth. Most plants die within 70 years. Species composition of the stands shifts without disturbance after that time (Tirmenstein 1989a). A fire return interval of 25-65 years should promote <i>Ceanothus leucodermis</i>.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
