    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ab-c). Small stands occur on nonserpentine substrates in the San Benito Mountains-Joaquin Ridge area in the Diablo Range (Evens et al. 2006). Although the species occurs elsewhere in this section, the alliance is not reported from Los Padres National Forest (Borchert et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eg, Ep, Es). Stands exist at low elevations of Sequoia (S. Haultain, pers. comm. 2003) and Yosemite (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) national parks.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-e). Stands occur in the southern foothills.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-h, Bk-p). Stand descriptions come from Fern Canyon and Hall Canyon RNAs (Cheng 2004), central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005), western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005), the San Bernardino Mountains (Minnich 1976), and generally in the section (Gordon and White 1994). Stands form at transitions between coastal scrub, chaparral, and conifer-oak forests. Recent burns in 2002 and 2003 on Volcan Mountain in San Diego Co. yielded mostly replacement of stands of the <i>Pseudotsuga macrocarpa</i> alliance with <i>C. leucodermis chaparral</i> (Gordon and White 1994).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Repeated short-interval fires (of < 25 years) deplete the seed bank of <i>Ceanothus leucodermis</i>. The genus <i>Ceanothus </i>is well suited for use in rehabilitation because of rapid growth rates and an ability to improve soil fertility through fixing nitrogen. </div>
</div>

    

    

